<DOC><DOCNO> AP880503-0116 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1305EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-CensusJobs     05-03 0242</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Census Jobs,230</SECOND><NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE><HEAD>Census Needs 35,000 Temporary Workers</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Help Wanted. Thirty-five thousand openings.Must be detail-oriented. Pays $5.50-an-hour, plus mileage. Outdoorwork, no heavy lifting.   The Census Bureau is gearing up for the 1990 national headcount, and it needs people to help compile the address list for usein mailing out the forms when the time comes.   Workers will go door-to-door to compile some 32 millionaddresses this year, and will add another 11 million next year,officials said Tuesday.   Most of the work is in counties away from metropolitan areas.Lists of the 56 million addresses in large cities are beingpurchased from commercial mailing-list companies.   Those compiling the address lists will work for about six weeks,the Census Bureau said, with the effort starting in July in 18states. The compilation will continue through December, moving toother states as the first ones are completed.   Applicants must take a written exam. Interested persons can getdetails from their local state employment office or by writingField Division, Room 3005-3, U.S. Census Bureau, Washington, D.C.20233.   The address list will be used to send census forms to householdsin the spring of 1990, and then to double check which ones havebeen returned and which require follow-up visits.   At that time an even bigger hiring effort is planned, becausesome 400,000 temporary workers will be needed for the census itself.</TEXT></DOC>